In general, an exception is something which does not adhere to a rule. You expect some things and they should mostly fulfill the expectations you have, but in some exceptional cases your expectations are not met. If you ponder about this, you will realize that since softwares can have different levels, what is an exception on a lower level is not necessarily an exception in higher level and vice-versa.

The main mistake you make in organizing your code is that your concern of index bounds is handled on the level of `findRoute` and not on its proper level, that is, in your `checkLeft` and `checkRight` methods. On the level of `findRoute`, you kind of expect to have some edge cases (literally), yet, on the level of `checkLeft` and `checkRight` you need to handle this. As a result, you should move all your concern about bounds into `checkLeft` and `checkRight`. If you see value in handling out of bounds as an exception for logging or any other purpose, then you can have a try-catch on the level of these methods, but you should ensure that they handle it. For example you can modify these methods to be `boolean` and return `true` at the end of the `try` and `false` at the end of the `catch`, `like`

    try {
        //Do some stuff
        return true;
    } catch (Exception e) {
        //Do some stuff
        return false;
    }

and then you can do something like this:

checkRight(area, row, col) || checkLeft(area, row, col);

Don&#39;t worry: if `checkRight` is `true`, `checkLeft` will not be called.

